The duties and powers of the judge

When assigned by the Chief Justice of the Court, the judges have the following tasks and powers:

1. Processing petitions;

2. Making administrative case files;

3. Verify and collect documents and evidence;organize trials and meetings to resolve administrative cases in accordance with this Law;

4. Deciding on the application, change and cancellation of temporary emergency measures;

5. Decision to suspend or temporarily suspend, decide to continue to bring administrative cases to settle;

6. Explain and guide the litigants so that they can exercise the right to request legal assistance in accordance with the law on legal aid;

7. Conducting a meeting to check the handover, approach and publicity of evidence and dialogue as prescribed by this Law;

8. Decision to bring administrative cases to trial;

9. Summon people participating in the trial, meeting;

10. Requires agencies, organizations and individuals to provide documents, evidence or verification, collection of documents and evidence in accordance with this Law;

11. The chairperson or joining the administrative case trial panel;vote issues under the jurisdiction of the Trial panel;

12. Considering the legality of administrative documents, administrative behaviors related to administrative decisions, administrative acts being sued and requesting the Chief Justice of the Court to propose to the competent agencies and individuals.The right to consider such administrative documents and acts in accordance with the law;

13. Detecting and proposing the Chief Justice of the Court to propose to the competent authority to consider, amend, supplement or abolish the legal documents showing signs against the Constitution, laws and regulationslaws of superior state agencies in accordance with this Law;

14. Handling acts of obstructing administrative procedure activities in accordance with law;

15. Perform other duties and powers as prescribed by this Law.

