Detecting and proposing amendments, supplements or abolishing legal documents

1. In the process of settling administrative cases, if detecting legal documents related to the settlement of administrative cases, signs that are contrary to the constitution, laws, legal documents of the agencyThe superior state, the Court implemented as follows:

a) In case there is no decision to bring the case to trial, the Chief Justice of the Court is resolving the case to make a petition according to its competence or request the competent person to be specified in Article 112 of this Law.recommendations;

b) In case of a decision to bring the case to trial or the case is being considered in the order of cassation or reopening, the Trial Council requests the Chief Justicerecommendations or request competent persons specified in Article 112 of this Law to make recommendations.

2. A written petition or request that the person competent to propose amendments, supplements or abolish legal documents must have the following main contents:

a) The name of the Court issued a written petition or proposal;

b) Summary of the contents of the case and legal issues posed to solve the case;

c) Name, number, date, month and year of the legal documents are proposed to amend, supplement or abolish them related to the settlement of the case;

d) Analyze the provisions of legal documents showing signs against the Constitution, laws and legal documents of superior state agencies;

d) Court's recommendations or proposals on amendments, supplements and abolishes such legal documents.

3. Attached to the petition or request that the person competent to propose is the legal document that is proposed amended, supplemented or abolished.

Petition

1. The petition must have the following main contents:

a) Date, month and year of application;

b) The Court is required to settle administrative cases;

c) Name and address;Phone number, fax number, email address (if any) of the petitioner, the lawsuit, the person with related rights and obligations;

d) Content of administrative decisions, disciplinary decisions forced jobs, decisions on settlement of complaints about decisions to handle competition cases, content of complaint settlement about the list of voters or summaries of developments ofadministrative acts;

d) Content of the decision to settle complaints (if any);

e) Requesting the Court to settle;

g) Guarantee not to complain to the person competent to settle complaints.

2. Attached to the petition must have documents and evidence proving the legitimate rights and interests of the petitioner.In case of objective reasons that the petitioner cannot fully submit all documents and evidence attached to the petition, they must submit the existing documents and evidence to prove the legal rights and interests of the initiator.The lawsuit is infringed.Other documents and evidence, the petitioner must supplement or supplement themselves at the request of the Court in the process of resolving the case.

