Return the petition

1. The judge returns the petition in the following cases:

a) The petitioner has no right to sue;

b) The petitioner does not have the capacity of full administrative proceedings;

c) In case the law provides for the conditions of lawsuits but the petitioner has sued the Court when there is a shortage of those conditions;

d) The incident has been resolved by the judgment or decision of the Court has taken legal effect;

d) The incident is not under the jurisdiction of the Court;

e) The petitioner selected to settle the case according to the complaint settlement procedure in the case of Article 33 of this Law;

g) The petition does not have enough contents prescribed in Clause 1, Article 118 of this Law without being amended and supplemented by the petitioner as prescribed in Article 122 of this Law;

h) Expiring time limit shall be notified specified in Clause 1, Article 125 of this Law, which the petitioner does not produce the receipt to pay the court fee advance to the Court, except for the case of the petitioner to be exempted from the advance payment.Fee, no payment of court fee advances or have a good reason.

2. When returning the petition and documents and evidence attached to the petitioner, the judge must have written clearly stating the reason for returning the petition.The written return of the petition was immediately sent to the Procuracy of the same level.

The petition and documents and evidence that the judge returned to the petitioner must be stared and saved in the Court as a basis for settling complaints and petitions when required.

Notice of accepting the case

1. Within 03 working days from the date of accepting the case, the judge has accepted the case, must notify in writing to the person who is sued, the person with interests and obligations related to the settlement of the case.And the Procuracy of the same level on the court has accepted the case and published on the Court's electronic portal (if any).

2. The notice must have the following main contents:

a) Date, month and year as a written notice;

b) Name and address of the Court has accepted the case;

c) Name and address of the petitioner, the lawsuit;

d) Specific issues of the petitioner asking the Court to settle;

d) The case is accepted according to normal procedures or shortened procedures;

e) List of documents and evidence of the petitioner submitted to the petition;

g) The time limit for lawsuits, people with relevant rights and obligations must submit comments in writing on the request of the petitioner and documents, evidence attached or independent requirements (if any) for the Courtsentence;

h) Legal consequences of the person who is sued, the person with related rights and obligations does not submit to the Court of written written records of his opinion on the request of the petitioner.

Terms to prepare for trial

The time limit for preparation for trials of cases, except for a case of shortened procedures, cases with foreign elements and cases of complaints on the list of voters are prescribed as follows:

1. 04 months from the date of accepting the case for the case specified at Point a, Clause 2, Article 116 of this Law;

2. 02 months from the date of accepting the case for the case specified at Point b, Clause 2, Article 116 of this Law;

3. For complicated cases or with objective obstacles, the Chief Justice of the Court may decide to extend the time limit for preparation for trial once, but not more than 02 months for the case specified in Clause 1 of this Article.and not exceeding 01 month for cases specified in Clause 2 of this Article;

4. In case of a decision to suspend the settlement of the case, the time limit for preparation is re -calculated from the date of the decision to continue resolving the case of the Court takes effect.

Principle of dialogue

1. Within the first instance trial, the Court conducts a dialogue for the litigants to agree with each other about the settlement of the case, except for cases where the case cannot be conducted, the case complaint about the nameVoter books, trial cases according to shortened procedures are specified in Articles 135, 198 and 246 of this Law.

2. The dialogue must be conducted according to the following principles:

a) Ensuring publicity, democracy and respect for the litigants' opinions;

b) Do not force the litigants to settle administrative cases contrary to their will;

c) Content of dialogue, results of conversation between the litigants is not illegal and contrary to social morality.

Composition of the meeting to check the handover, approach, publicity of evidence and dialogue

1. Participating components include:

a) The judge presides over the meeting;

b) Secretary of the meeting record;

c) The litigant or legal representative of the litigant;

d) The person who defends the legal rights and interests of the involved parties (if any);

d) Interpreter (if any).

2. In case of necessity, the judge has the right to request the concerned agencies, organizations and individuals to attend the meeting.

3. In the case, there are many litigants, but there are involved parties, but the litigants are present and agree to conduct the meeting and the conduct of that meeting does not affect the rights and obligations of the involved parties.then the judge conducted a meeting between the involved parties;If the involved parties propose to postpone the meeting to be present to all the litigants in the case, the judge must postpone the meeting and notify in writing the postponement of the meeting, reopening the meeting for the litigants.

The order of sessions to check the handover, approach, disclosure of evidence and dialogue

1. Before opening the meeting, the secretary of the press conference reported the judge on the presence and absence of the participants in the meeting were notified by the Court.The judge presides over the meeting to check the presence and identity of participants, disseminating to the litigants to know the rights and obligations in accordance with this Law.

2. When conducting the inspection of the handover, approach, publicity of evidence, the judge publishes documents and evidence in the case file and asked the litigant on the following issues:

a) Requirements and scope of lawsuits, amendments, supplements, replacement and withdrawal of lawsuits;independent requirements;agreed issues, issues that have not agreed on the Court to solve;

b) The handover of documents and evidence to the Court and the sending of other documents and evidence to other litigants;

c) The addition of documents, evidence and proposals of the Court to collect documents, evidence and summon other litigants, witnesses and other participants at the trial;

d) Other issues that the involved parties are necessary.

3. After the involved parties are completed, the judge reviews the opinions and resolves the involved parties' proposals specified in Clause 2 of this Article;In case the involved parties are absent, the court notifies the results of the meeting for them.

4. After completing the inspection, approaching and publicizing the evidence specified in Clause 2 of this Article, the Judges conduct the following dialogue procedures:

a) The judge disseminates the litigants the provisions of the law related to the settlement of the case so that the parties will contact their rights and obligations, analyze the legal consequences of the dialogue for themvoluntarily agree on the settlement of the case;

b) Additional lawsuiters on the request of lawsuits and bases to protect the request of the lawsuit and propose the petitioner's views on the direction of the case settlement (if any);

c) The person who is sued is supplemented with the request of the petitioner, the bases for issuing administrative decisions, committing administrative acts that are sued and propose to the case resolution (if any);

d) Persons with rights and obligations related to the case of additional presentation and propose opinions to solve them related to them (if any);

d) The defender of the legitimate rights and interests of the litigants or others participating in the dialogue meeting (if any) expressed their opinions;

e) Depending on the case, the judge asks the involved parties to state the legal documents and relevant administrative documents to assess the legality of the administrative decision, the administrative acts that are sued, and at the same timeCheck the legal effect of that document.The judge may analyze so that the involved parties are properly aware of the contents of the relevant legal documents and administrative documents so that they can choose and decide on the settlement of the case;

g) After the involved parties present their opinions, the judge identifies the agreed issues, the inconsistent issues and asking the parties to present to the contents yet.clear, not unified;

h) The judge concludes that the issues of the parties have agreed and unanimous issues.

5. Secretary of the meeting records the minutes of the meeting to check the handover, approach, publicity of evidence and dialogue.

Minutes of the meeting to check the handover, approach and disclosure of evidence;Dialogue minutes

1. Minutes of the meeting to check the handover, approach and disclosure of evidence must have the following contents:

a) Date, month and year conduct the meeting;

b) The site of the meeting;

c) Composition of the meeting;

d) The opinions of the litigants or the legal representative of the litigant, the person who protects the litigant's legitimate rights and interests on the contents specified in Clause 2, Article 138 of this Law;

d) Other contents;

e) The judge's conclusion about accepting, not accepting the involved parties' proposals.

2. The minutes of dialogue must have the following contents:

a) The contents specified at Points a, b and c, Clause 1 of this Article;

b) The opinions of the litigants or legal representatives of the litigants, the defending the legitimate rights and interests of the litigants;

c) The content has been unified and unified by the litigant.

3. For cases where the dialogue is not conducted in Article 135 of this Law shall make a record as prescribed in Clause 1 of this Article.

4. The minutes must have all the signatures or points of the participants, the signature of the Secretary of the meeting recorded the minutes and the judge chaired the meeting.The participants of the meeting have the right to see the meeting minutes right after the end of the meeting, request to write the amendments and add to the meeting minutes and sign the name or point of confirmation.

Temporarily suspend the settlement of the case

1. The Court decides to suspend the settlement of the case when one of the following cases:

a) The involved parties are dead individuals, agencies and organizations have dissolved or declared bankrupt without individuals, agencies and organizations inheriting the rights and obligations of the proceedings;

b) The litigant is a person who has lost civil act capacity, minors but has not yet identified legal representatives;

c) Expiring time limit for trial preparation that one of the litigants cannot be present for plausible reasons, except for cases where the trial may be absent;

d) It is necessary to wait for the settlement results of other agencies or the results of other relevant cases;

d) It is necessary to wait for additional assessment and re -assessment results;It is necessary to wait for the results of the judicial entrustment, the entrusted to collect evidence or wait for agencies and organizations to provide documents and evidence at the request of the Court to resolve the case;

e) It is necessary to wait for the results of handling legal documents related to the settlement of cases indicating signs against the constitution, laws, legal documents of superior state agencies that the Court has existed.Written petitions to competent agencies to consider amending, supplementing or abolishing that document.

2. The decision to suspend the settlement of the case may be appealed and protested according to the appellate procedure.

