Handling acts that hinder the verification and collection of evidence of the Court

Those who have one of the following acts, depending on the nature and seriousness of the violation, may be disciplined, sanctioned administrative violations or being examined for penal liability in accordance with the law:

1. Countering and destroying important evidence interfere with the resolution of the Court's case;

2. To refuse to declare, deceive or provide false documents when testifying;

3. Refuse to conclude the assessment or refuse to provide documents without plausible reasons, concluding false assessments;

4. Deception, threat, coercion, bribe and use force to prevent witnesses from doing witnesses or forcing others to witness to deceit;

5. Deception, threat, coercion, bribe and use force in order to prevent the assessment from performing the task or forcing the assessor to conclude wrongly with the objective truth;

6. Deception, threat, coercion, bribe, use force to prevent the interpreter performing the mission or forcing the interpreters to be dishonest, not objective, not true;

7. Hearing the person conducting the proceedings of the review, on -site appraisal, decision on pricing, decision to solicit assessment or verify and collect other evidence in accordance with this Law;

8. Deliberately translating the truth;

9. Do not send people to participate in the valuation council at the request of the Court without plausible reasons;Do not participate in performing the duties of the valuation council without plausible reasons.

Handling acts that hinder the delivery, receipt, grant, expel or notice of the Court's legal documents

People with one of the following acts, depending on the nature and seriousness of the violation, are disciplined, sanctioned administrative violations or being examined for penal liability in accordance with the law:

1. Failing to grant, assign, expel or notify the Court's legal documents at the request of the Court without plausible reasons;

2. Destroying the proceedings of the Court that they are assigned to issue, expel or notify the Court's request;

3. Forging the results of the implementation of the Court's proceedings of the Court that they were assigned to implement;

4. Preventing the granting, assigning, receiving, serving or notifying the Court's legal documents.

